The '''geology of the [[Cayman Islands]]''' includes carbonates deposited and periodically eroded over the last 30&nbsp;million years. The underlying Cayman Ridge is proposed as an uplifted fault block. The oldest rocks are believed to be [[granodiorite]], followed by a cap of [[basalt]].<ref>https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=VKP6CAAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PR7&dq=geology+of+the+cayman+islands&ots=h-5TmH1huq&sig=JKQznvbyJrndB3lb19GLq5-ZGJs#v=onepage&q=geology%20of%20the%20cayman%20islands&f=false</ref> Situated near the Oriente Transform Fault and the Mid-Cayman Rise, the islands are tectonically active.<ref name="springer">{{cite web|url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-94-011-0904-8_2|title=Geology of the Cayman Islands|website=SpringerLink|accessdate=2018-11-09}}</ref> Older [[Miocene]] and [[Pliocene]] crystalline limestone is overlain by the [[Pleistocene]] Ironshore Formation reef limestone and [[calcarenite]].<ref name="cambridge">{{cite web|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/geological-magazine/article/pleistocene-rocks-of-the-cayman-islands/9E1EE541748572542DAE55BC36AC8B05|title=The Pleistocene rocks of the Cayman Islands &#124; Geological Magazine &#124; Cambridge Core|website=cambridge.org|accessdate=2018-11-09}}</ref>
