{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Lipstick Jihad: A Memoir of Growing Up Iranian in America and American in Iran | title_orig = | translator = | image = Lipstick Jihad.jpg| caption = | author = [[Azadeh Moaveni]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = Iranian American women | genre = Biography | publisher = [[PublicAffairs|Public Affairs]] | pub_date = 2005 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 249 | isbn = 1-58648-193-2 | isbn_note = <ref name="powells"/> | dewey= 305.48/89155073/092 B 22 | congress= E184.I5 M63 2005 | oclc= 56617255 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Lipstick Jihad: A Memoir of Growing Up Iranian in America and American in Iran''''' ({{ISBN|1-58648-193-2}}) is [[Iranian-American]] writer [[Azadeh Moaveni]]'s first book, published on February 4, 2005.<ref name="powells"/>
The book tells the story of her first-person experiences in [[Iran]] where she worked as a reporter after living in the United States her entire life.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/discussion/2006/05/15/DI2006051501234.html |title=Lipstick Jihad |date=23 May 2006 |publisher=[[The Washington Post]] }}</ref><ref name="motherjones">{{cite web |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2005/03/lipstick-jihad-interview-azadeh-moaveni |title=An interview with Azadeh Moaveni|date=9 March 2005 |publisher=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] }}</ref> The book is part of a growing movement of female writers within the [[Iranian diaspora]], including such other authors as [[Marjane Satrapi]], [[Firoozeh Dumas]], [[Nahid Rachlin]], and [[Azar Nafisi]].<ref name="powells">{{cite web |url=http://www.powells.com/biblio/9781586481933 |title=Lipstick Jihad |accessdate=23 March 2014 |publisher=Powell's Books }}</ref>
