{{Infobox settlement | name = Meherabad | native_name = | native_name_lang = | other_name = | settlement_type = town | image_skyline = Meher Baba samadhi 2.jpg | image_alt = | image_caption = Faredoon Driver shows the grounds of Upper Meherabad. | nickname = | map_alt = | map_caption = | pushpin_map = India Maharashtra#India | pushpin_label_position = right | pushpin_map_alt = | pushpin_map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|19.029539|N|74.719042|E|display=inline,title}} | subdivision_type = Country | subdivision_name = India | subdivision_type1 = [[States and territories of India|State]] | subdivision_name1 = [[Maharashtra]] | subdivision_type2 = [[List of districts of India|District]] | subdivision_name2 = [[Ahmednagar district|Ahmednagar]] | established_title = <!-- Established --> | established_date = | founder = | named_for = | government_type = | governing_body = | unit_pref = Metric | area_footnotes = | area_rank = | area_total_km2 = | elevation_footnotes = | elevation_m = 672 | population_total = | population_as_of = | population_rank = | population_density_km2 = auto | population_demonym = | population_footnotes = | timezone1 = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]] | utc_offset1 = +5:30 | postal_code_type = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] | postal_code = 414001 | registration_plate = | website = {{URL|ambppct.org}} | footnotes = }}
'''Meherabad''' (''meher'' meaning "friend" from Iranian "Mihir", ultimately from Sanskrit "Mithira"; ''abad'' meaning a prosperous settlement, or a flourishing colony) was originally an [[ashram]] established by [[Meher Baba]] near Arangaon Village, [[India]] in 1923 about {{convert|9|km|0}} south of [[Ahmednagar]]. It is now the site of [[Samadhi of Meher Baba|Meher Baba's samadhi]] (shrine/tomb) as well as facilities and accommodations for [[pilgrim]]s. A large number of buildings mostly associated with the earlier decades of Baba’s work, the graves of disciples, and a range of pilgrim accommodation and charitable establishments are also there. Many Baba-lovers work or live in the vicinity.<ref>''Avatar Meher Baba, His Life, His Message and His Followers,'' Copyright 1996 Ray Kerkhove, Peter Milne and Ray Kerkhove,</ref>
Meherabad is a popular place of [[pilgrimage]] for both Eastern and Western followers of Meher Baba, with reported numbers of around 30,000 annual pilgrims at [[Amartithi]] (the commemoration of his death each January 31).<ref>Meher Baba Trust - Calendar of Events {{cite web |url=http://www.ambppct.org/events/events.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-04-04 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423035553/http://www.ambppct.org/events/events.php |archivedate=2008-04-23 |df= }}</ref> There is also a [[free dispensary]] and school.
Established in May 1923, Meherabad was the first permanent residence of Meher Baba and his disciples in [[Ahmednagar district]].<ref>''Meher Prabhu: Lord Meher, The Biography of the Avatar of the Age, Meher Baba,'' by Bhau Kalchuri, Manifestation, Inc. 1986. p. 519</ref> In 1944, Meher Baba moved his residence north to [[Meherazad]], located {{convert|24|km|0}} away on the other side of Ahmedagar.<ref>Meher Baba's Last Sahavas, pp. 15-16 Copyright 1969 Dr. H. P. Bharucha</ref>
'''Meher Pilgrim Center''' (also spelled "Centre") is the central administrative facility for the [[Meher Baba]] pilgrim [[Retreat (spiritual)|retreat]].The Pilgrim Center and Pilgrim Retreat are closed during the hot Indian summer from 15 March to 15 June of each year.On 15 June 2006, new pilgrim facilities were established with the construction of '''Meher Pilgrim Retreat''', an {{convert|88000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} facility.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ambppct.org/inhisservice/IHS_NL_98_Dec.pdf# |title=In His Service, A Newsletter from Meherabad, December 1998 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304044258/http://ambppct.org/inhisservice/IHS_NL_98_Dec.pdf# |archive-date=4 March 2016 |dead-url=no |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Both the Pilgrim Center and Pilgrim Retreat were designed by architect Ted Judson.
